  "opinion": "As a young woman in Los Angeles who works retail and has a background shaped by my parents' education levels—my father with a vocational diploma and my mother with only lower secondary schooling—I see the gender gap in science not as a simple binary but as a complex web of systemic barriers woven into the fabric of opportunity. Growing up in a household where formal education beyond high school wasn’t prioritized, I’ve witnessed how societal expectations can steer girls away from STEM fields early on. My own anxiety often makes me overthink whether I belong in spaces dominated by people who seem to know more than me, but I’ve found solace in the quiet moments of birdwatching and running, activities that teach me patience and observation—skills that are surprisingly relevant to scientific thinking. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers; it’s about who gets to ask questions and who gets to answer them. I believe we should address it, but not with top-down solutions that ignore the lived experiences of those who’ve been marginalized. Instead, we need grassroots efforts that start in classrooms and community centers, where teachers can see the potential in every student without the pressure of fitting into a narrow mold. My high extraversion means I thrive in social settings, but my low conscientiousness reminds me to slow down and listen deeply. In a world where science is increasingly vital, I think we must create spaces where everyone feels safe to explore their curiosity without fear of judgment. It’s not about fixing what’s broken but building bridges where everyone can contribute meaningfully.",
